This doesn't work because MerkleMap is not a "provable" type.  So even if I do have the whole map, I can't use it in a proof.  Would I need to extract a merkle proof outside of the circuit with something like

```
const myKey = Poseidon.hash(someAddress.toFields())
const myProof = myMap.getWitness(myKey);
```

How do I actually use this proof?  Still can't really wrap my head around it.  What I want to do seems basic: assert that the previous balance of the player is `x`, increase the value by `y` , and obtain a new proof that the value is `x + y`.

And I'm also still trying to figure out what the empty state looks like.  From the merkle tree example:

```
// we check that the account is within the committed Merkle Tree
path.calculateRoot(account.hash()).assertEquals(root);
```

This makes it seem like to use a merkle tree I need to know the accounts of all of my user a priori so that they can create merkle witnesses.  But what if I start with no users and add them over time?

This implementation is working for now, thanks all!

```
  @method
  deposit(
    player: PublicKey,
    amount: Field,
    previousBalance: Field,
    witness: MerkleMapWitness
  ) {
    const stateMapRoot = this.merkleMapRoot.get();
    this.merkleMapRoot.assertEquals(stateMapRoot);

    let witnessRoot: Field;
    let witnessKey: Field;
    [witnessRoot, witnessKey] = witness.computeRootAndKey(previousBalance);

    const playerKey = Poseidon.hash(player.toFields());

    // Assert that the merkle map we are pulling out of our hat is valid
    this.merkleMapRoot.assertEquals(witnessRoot);
    playerKey.assertEquals(witnessKey);

    const depositUpdate = AccountUpdate.create(player);
    depositUpdate.send({ to: this.address, amount: new UInt64(amount) });

    [witnessRoot, witnessKey] = witness.computeRootAndKey(
      previousBalance.add(amount)
    );
    this.merkleMapRoot.set(witnessRoot);
  }
```

I foresee running into some more of the issues that we discussed but at least this will "work" while I can stew about more nuanced approaches.

